	&lt;li&gt;Each collection as a whole (no sharding) is simply replicated by the other node.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One node is leader for 3, the other node for 2 collections.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;However, the error only shows up at the node that is leader for 3 collections.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16934336" author="aheaven" created="Fri, 20 Sep 2019 12:09:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=kstoney&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;kstoney&quot;&gt;kstoney&lt;/a&gt;, does this error break anything? I am seeing these errors in production so just curious. Thank you.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16947537" author="caomanhdat" created="Wed, 9 Oct 2019 10:39:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi guys,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem here happened since in &lt;tt&gt;SolrCmdDistributor.Req.getRfFromResponse()&lt;/tt&gt; the &lt;tt&gt;InputStream&lt;/tt&gt; (passed by ConcurrentUpdateHttp2SolrClient) had been closed then the client was tried to fully consume it before closing it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What are consequences of this problem? &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;People get panic about error log like this &lt;tt&gt;Error consuming and closing http response stream&lt;/tt&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;That is the only problem since &lt;tt&gt;SolrCmdDistributor.Req.getRfFromResponse&lt;/tt&gt; already fully consume the request before closing it. &lt;br/&gt;
That problem already happens in previous versions of Solr but &lt;tt&gt;ConcurrentUpdateSolrClient&lt;/tt&gt; just quietly catch the exception.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My propose for this problem is stopping close() the &lt;tt&gt;InputStream&lt;/tt&gt; in  &lt;tt&gt;SolrCmdDistributor.Req.getRfFromResponse&lt;/tt&gt; and note to users that the InputStream passed by &lt;tt&gt;ConcurrentUpdateHttp2SolrClient&lt;/tt&gt; should not be closed.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16947538" author="caomanhdat" created="Wed, 9 Oct 2019 10:40:13 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Attached a patch for this issue, tests already passed! Will commit soon.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
